{{expand language|topic=|langcode=it|otherarticle=Tratturo Pescasseroli-Candela|date=October 2013}}
[[File:Tratturo-Pescasseroli-Candela.jpg|right|frame|Map of major drovers' roads in southern Italy, with Tratturo Pescasseroli-Candela highlighted in red]]
The '''Tratturo Pescasseroli-Candela''' is a [[drovers' road]] running between [[Pescasseroli]] in [[Abruzzo]] and [[Candela, Apulia|Candela]] in [[Apulia]]. It is the third longest such route in southern Italy.<ref name="Haines2012">{{cite book|author=Stuart Haines|title=Walking in Abruzzo|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=RQFNCBLe1AsC&pg=PA106|date=14 June 2012|publisher=Cicerone Press Limited|isbn=978-1-84965-688-7|pages=106–}}</ref>

== Geography ==
The Tratturo Pescasseroli-Candela runs between [[Pescasseroli]] in [[Abruzzo]] and [[Candela, Apulia|Candela]] in [[Apulia]], covering a distance of {{convert|211|km}}, and is up to {{convert|60|m}} wide along some stretches.<ref name="BouetOtranto2007">{{cite book|author1=[[Pierre Bouet]] | author2=Giorgio Otranto|author3=André Vauchez|title=Culte et sanctuaires de saint Michel dans l'Europe médiévale|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=mK2UeJObpd8C&pg=PA326|year=2007|publisher=Edipuglia srl|language=Italian|isbn=978-88-7228-501-5|pages=326–}}</ref>

It is still used for seasonal migration of herds. Some historians, such as Wisemann, believe that it follows the same route as the [[Via Traiana|Via Minucia Traiana]], an ancient Roman road.

