'''Wacław Zygmunt Anczyc''' (born February 4, 1866 in [[Warsaw]], died. September 27, 1938 in [[Kraków]]) was a [[Polish people|Polish]] [[printer (publishing)|printer]] and [[historian]], son of [[Władysław Ludwik Anczyc]].<ref>Encyklopedia popularna PWN, wyd. 27, Warszawa 1997, s. 33.</ref> He studied history at the [[Jagiellonian University]] Faculty of [[Literature]] and in [[Leipzig]]. After 1883, when his father died, he inherited a [[printing press]] in Kraków. In 1900 he moved his printing press to the [[monastery]] of the Resurrection. He expanded and modernized the industry, making a large contribution to the development of printing in [[Poland]].<ref name="Sienkiewicz1977">{{cite book|last=Sienkiewicz|first=Henryk|title=Listy|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=okdIAAAAIAAJ|accessdate=15 July 2012|year=1977|publisher=Państwowy Instytut Wydawniczy|page=43}}</ref> In 1908 he founded a compulsory [[school]] for students of printing in Kraków.

